<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1184,2037]" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">
<mcCollectionCode box="[151,282,1185,1208]" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">DEFINITION</mcCollectionCode>
<mcCollectionCode box="[290,318,1188,1207]" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">OF</mcCollectionCode>
<mcCollectionCode box="[327,371,1188,1207]" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">THE</mcCollectionCode>
SUBGENUS. Small to medium-sized (3.5–9.0), convex or flattened, subparallel, often elongate species (
<figureCitation box="[247,385,1220,1245]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–24" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1851,1874]" captionTargetBox="[165,1426,219,1796]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1435,205,1810]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 13–24. Anthaxia, dorsal aspect. 13—Anthaxia (Melanthaxia) kochi Obenberger, male, 6.5 mm; 14- A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug), male, 6.1 mm; 15—A. (R.) congolana Kerremans, male, 11.0 mm; 16—A. (R.) marginifera metallescens Bílý, male, 9.1 mm; 17—A. (Merocratus) miranda Deyrolle, female, 8.0 mm; 18—A. (Thailandica.) rondoni Baudon, 5.5 mm; 19—A. (Capanthaxia) capensis Kerremans, lectotype, 3.9 mm; 20—the same, male, blue form, 4.5 mm; 21—A. (Cap.) hilaris Gory, female, 4.8 mm; 22—A. (Cap.) aterrima Kerremans, male, 7.1 mm; 23—A. (Cap.) sulcicollis Obenberger, male, 4.0 mm; 24—the same, female, 5.8 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599422/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">Figs. 19–24</figureCitation>
); frons weakly convex or flat, vertex 0.8–2.0 times as wide as width of eye; antennae short or very short, not overlapping pronotal midlength when laid alongside, antennomeres of male not widened; sculpture of head consisting of very small, dense, oval cells without distinct central grains.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1184,2037]" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">
Pronotum moderately convex or flattened with medial, longitudinal depression or groove (
<figureCitation box="[1280,1424,1328,1353]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–24" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1851,1874]" captionTargetBox="[165,1426,219,1796]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1435,205,1810]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 13–24. Anthaxia, dorsal aspect. 13—Anthaxia (Melanthaxia) kochi Obenberger, male, 6.5 mm; 14- A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug), male, 6.1 mm; 15—A. (R.) congolana Kerremans, male, 11.0 mm; 16—A. (R.) marginifera metallescens Bílý, male, 9.1 mm; 17—A. (Merocratus) miranda Deyrolle, female, 8.0 mm; 18—A. (Thailandica.) rondoni Baudon, 5.5 mm; 19—A. (Capanthaxia) capensis Kerremans, lectotype, 3.9 mm; 20—the same, male, blue form, 4.5 mm; 21—A. (Cap.) hilaris Gory, female, 4.8 mm; 22—A. (Cap.) aterrima Kerremans, male, 7.1 mm; 23—A. (Cap.) sulcicollis Obenberger, male, 4.0 mm; 24—the same, female, 5.8 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599422/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">Figs. 19–24</figureCitation>
); posterior angles rectangular or weakly obtuse-angled, maximum width at anterior third; sculpture consisting of transverse or weakly undulate rugae on disc and irregular, polygonal cells with tiny central grains along lateral margins (
<figureCitation box="[260,402,1436,1461]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–54" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1837,1860]" captionTargetBox="[165,1425,353,1806]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1435,339,1815]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 40–54. Anthaxia, pronotal sculpture (not in scale). 40—Anthaxia (Anthaxia) fulgurans (Schrank); 41—A. (A.) salicis salicis (Fabricius); 42—A. (A.) manca (Fabricius); 43—A. (Melanthaxia) nigrojubata nigrojubata Roubal; 44—A. (Cratomerus) hungarica hungarica (Scopoli); 45—A. (Haplanthaxia) cichorii (Olivier); 46—A. (H.) kneuckeri zabranskyi Bílý; 47—A. (H.) pumila (Klug); 48—A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug); 49—A. (R.) marginifera metallescens Bílý; 50— A. (Merocratus) tamdaoensis Bílý; 51—A. (Thailandia) rondoni Baudon; 52—A. (Capanthaxia) capensis Kerremans; 53—A. (Cap.) aterrima Kerremans; 54—A. (Cap.) sulcicollis Obenberger." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599428/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">Figs. 52–54</figureCitation>
); lateroposterior depressions shallow but wide, sometimes prolonged anteriorly, reaching anterior pronotal third; prescutellar pit absent. Scutellum very small, triangular or cordiform, only slightly longer than wide.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1184,2037]" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">
Elytra moderately convex or flattened, very often uneven (
<figureCitation box="[889,974,1544,1569]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–24" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1851,1874]" captionTargetBox="[165,1426,219,1796]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1435,205,1810]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 13–24. Anthaxia, dorsal aspect. 13—Anthaxia (Melanthaxia) kochi Obenberger, male, 6.5 mm; 14- A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug), male, 6.1 mm; 15—A. (R.) congolana Kerremans, male, 11.0 mm; 16—A. (R.) marginifera metallescens Bílý, male, 9.1 mm; 17—A. (Merocratus) miranda Deyrolle, female, 8.0 mm; 18—A. (Thailandica.) rondoni Baudon, 5.5 mm; 19—A. (Capanthaxia) capensis Kerremans, lectotype, 3.9 mm; 20—the same, male, blue form, 4.5 mm; 21—A. (Cap.) hilaris Gory, female, 4.8 mm; 22—A. (Cap.) aterrima Kerremans, male, 7.1 mm; 23—A. (Cap.) sulcicollis Obenberger, male, 4.0 mm; 24—the same, female, 5.8 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599422/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
) or with traces of longitudinal rows of punctures (
<figureCitation box="[278,417,1580,1605]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–24" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1851,1874]" captionTargetBox="[165,1426,219,1796]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1435,205,1810]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 13–24. Anthaxia, dorsal aspect. 13—Anthaxia (Melanthaxia) kochi Obenberger, male, 6.5 mm; 14- A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug), male, 6.1 mm; 15—A. (R.) congolana Kerremans, male, 11.0 mm; 16—A. (R.) marginifera metallescens Bílý, male, 9.1 mm; 17—A. (Merocratus) miranda Deyrolle, female, 8.0 mm; 18—A. (Thailandica.) rondoni Baudon, 5.5 mm; 19—A. (Capanthaxia) capensis Kerremans, lectotype, 3.9 mm; 20—the same, male, blue form, 4.5 mm; 21—A. (Cap.) hilaris Gory, female, 4.8 mm; 22—A. (Cap.) aterrima Kerremans, male, 7.1 mm; 23—A. (Cap.) sulcicollis Obenberger, male, 4.0 mm; 24—the same, female, 5.8 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599422/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">Figs. 19–21</figureCitation>
), apically widely rounded and somewhat shortened so that the pygidium is often visible from above (
<figureCitation box="[302,444,1616,1641]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–24" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1851,1874]" captionTargetBox="[165,1426,219,1796]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1435,205,1810]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 13–24. Anthaxia, dorsal aspect. 13—Anthaxia (Melanthaxia) kochi Obenberger, male, 6.5 mm; 14- A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug), male, 6.1 mm; 15—A. (R.) congolana Kerremans, male, 11.0 mm; 16—A. (R.) marginifera metallescens Bílý, male, 9.1 mm; 17—A. (Merocratus) miranda Deyrolle, female, 8.0 mm; 18—A. (Thailandica.) rondoni Baudon, 5.5 mm; 19—A. (Capanthaxia) capensis Kerremans, lectotype, 3.9 mm; 20—the same, male, blue form, 4.5 mm; 21—A. (Cap.) hilaris Gory, female, 4.8 mm; 22—A. (Cap.) aterrima Kerremans, male, 7.1 mm; 23—A. (Cap.) sulcicollis Obenberger, male, 4.0 mm; 24—the same, female, 5.8 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599422/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">Figs. 19–24</figureCitation>
); humeral callosities small, not projecting beyond elytral outline; lateral, longitudinal groove well-developed, its preapical part deep, very often with large, strong punctures (
<figureCitation box="[1146,1284,1652,1677]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–24" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1851,1874]" captionTargetBox="[165,1426,219,1796]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1435,205,1810]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 13–24. Anthaxia, dorsal aspect. 13—Anthaxia (Melanthaxia) kochi Obenberger, male, 6.5 mm; 14- A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug), male, 6.1 mm; 15—A. (R.) congolana Kerremans, male, 11.0 mm; 16—A. (R.) marginifera metallescens Bílý, male, 9.1 mm; 17—A. (Merocratus) miranda Deyrolle, female, 8.0 mm; 18—A. (Thailandica.) rondoni Baudon, 5.5 mm; 19—A. (Capanthaxia) capensis Kerremans, lectotype, 3.9 mm; 20—the same, male, blue form, 4.5 mm; 21—A. (Cap.) hilaris Gory, female, 4.8 mm; 22—A. (Cap.) aterrima Kerremans, male, 7.1 mm; 23—A. (Cap.) sulcicollis Obenberger, male, 4.0 mm; 24—the same, female, 5.8 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599422/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">Figs. 19–21</figureCitation>
); subhumeral lobe large, lateral emargination deep (
<figureCitation box="[572,655,1688,1713]" captionStart="FIGURES 25–39" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1832,1855]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,742,1802]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[150,1437,733,1811]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 25–39. Anthaxia, subhumeral lobe (not in scale). 25—Anthaxia (Richteraxia) amplithorax Kerremans, white arrow indicates “lock&quot; in humeral callosity; 26—A. (Anthaxia) salicis salicis (Fabricius); 27—A. (A.) fulgurans (Schrank); 28—A. (A.) plicata plicata Kiesenwetter; 29—A. (A.) stepanovi Richter, holotype; 30—A. (Cratomerus) hungarica hungarica (Scopoli); 31—A. (Haplanthaxia) cichorii (Olivier); 32—A. (H.) caseyi Obenberger; 33—A. (H.) dispar Kerremans; 34—A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug); 35—A. (Melanthaxia) quadripunctata (Linnaeus); 36—A. (M.) kochi Obenberger; 37—A. (Merocratus) insulaecola Obenberger; 38—A. (Thailandia.) rondoni Baudon; 39—A. (Capanthzaxia..) hilaris Gory." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599424/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
); elytral epipleura usually enlarged posteriorly almost reaching elytral apex; sculpture consisting of fine punctures (sometimes forming longitudinal rows on apical half of elytra—Figs. 19–20), or fine, transverse rugae (
<figureCitation box="[530,667,1760,1785]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–24" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1851,1874]" captionTargetBox="[165,1426,219,1796]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1435,205,1810]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 13–24. Anthaxia, dorsal aspect. 13—Anthaxia (Melanthaxia) kochi Obenberger, male, 6.5 mm; 14- A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug), male, 6.1 mm; 15—A. (R.) congolana Kerremans, male, 11.0 mm; 16—A. (R.) marginifera metallescens Bílý, male, 9.1 mm; 17—A. (Merocratus) miranda Deyrolle, female, 8.0 mm; 18—A. (Thailandica.) rondoni Baudon, 5.5 mm; 19—A. (Capanthaxia) capensis Kerremans, lectotype, 3.9 mm; 20—the same, male, blue form, 4.5 mm; 21—A. (Cap.) hilaris Gory, female, 4.8 mm; 22—A. (Cap.) aterrima Kerremans, male, 7.1 mm; 23—A. (Cap.) sulcicollis Obenberger, male, 4.0 mm; 24—the same, female, 5.8 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599422/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">Figs. 23, 24</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1184,2037]" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">Legs moderately long, male tibiae simple, not modified, only with fine, inner serrations; tarsal claws simple, not widened at base; anal ventrite of both sexes regularly rounded, without lateral serrations.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1184,2037]" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">
Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[326,408,1868,1893]" captionStart="FIGURES 55–76" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1812,1835]" captionTargetBox="[155,1426,217,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[150,1436,203,1771]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 55–76. Anthaxia, aedeagi (not in scale). 55—Anthaxia (Anthaxia) candens (Panzer); 56—A. (A.) kmoniceki Bílý; 57—A. (Melanthaxia) nigrojubata incognita Bílý; 58—A. (M.) helvetica Stierlin; 59—A. (M.) obesa Abeille; 60—A. (Cratomerus) hungarica hungarica (Scopoli); 61—A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug); 62—A. (R.) crassa Obenberger; 63—A. (R.) imperatrix Obenberger; 64—A. (Haplanthaxia) elaeagni Richter; 65—A. (H.) nigroaenea Bílý; 66—A. (H.) pseudocongregata Descarpentries; 67—A. (H.) kneuckeri zabranskyi Bílý; 68—A. (H.) deimos Bílý; 69—A. (H.) dispar Kerremans; 70—A. (H.) loebli Bílý; 71—A. (H.) thailandica Bílý; 72—A. (H.) occulta Bílý; 73—A. (H.) duodevicesima Bílý; 74—A. (Merocratus) longipilis Bílý; 75—A. (Thailandica) rondoni; 76—A. (Capanthaxia) capensis Kerremans." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599430/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">Fig. 76</figureCitation>
) rather short, spindle-shaped, parameres without lateral spines, often widened at basal two thirds, median lobe without lateral serrations.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1184,2037]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1436,151,680]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="269" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">
DIFFERENTIAL DIAGNOSIS. The subgenus is characterised first of all by the pronotal sculpture with the longitudinal, medial depression, transverse or somewhat undulate rugae which cover the entire pronotal disc (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 40–54" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1837,1860]" captionTargetBox="[165,1425,353,1806]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1435,339,1815]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 40–54. Anthaxia, pronotal sculpture (not in scale). 40—Anthaxia (Anthaxia) fulgurans (Schrank); 41—A. (A.) salicis salicis (Fabricius); 42—A. (A.) manca (Fabricius); 43—A. (Melanthaxia) nigrojubata nigrojubata Roubal; 44—A. (Cratomerus) hungarica hungarica (Scopoli); 45—A. (Haplanthaxia) cichorii (Olivier); 46—A. (H.) kneuckeri zabranskyi Bílý; 47—A. (H.) pumila (Klug); 48—A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug); 49—A. (R.) marginifera metallescens Bílý; 50— A. (Merocratus) tamdaoensis Bílý; 51—A. (Thailandia) rondoni Baudon; 52—A. (Capanthaxia) capensis Kerremans; 53—A. (Cap.) aterrima Kerremans; 54—A. (Cap.) sulcicollis Obenberger." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599428/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="268">Figs. 52–54</figureCitation>
); only lateral parts of pronotum along the lateral margins (sometimes only the posterior angles) with rough polygonal, often prolonged cells. Another, very typical character is the shape of the elytral apex which is usually widely rounded, not completely covering the pygidium, with the deep lateral groove (
<figureCitation box="[1107,1246,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–24" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1851,1874]" captionTargetBox="[165,1426,219,1796]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1435,205,1810]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 13–24. Anthaxia, dorsal aspect. 13—Anthaxia (Melanthaxia) kochi Obenberger, male, 6.5 mm; 14- A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug), male, 6.1 mm; 15—A. (R.) congolana Kerremans, male, 11.0 mm; 16—A. (R.) marginifera metallescens Bílý, male, 9.1 mm; 17—A. (Merocratus) miranda Deyrolle, female, 8.0 mm; 18—A. (Thailandica.) rondoni Baudon, 5.5 mm; 19—A. (Capanthaxia) capensis Kerremans, lectotype, 3.9 mm; 20—the same, male, blue form, 4.5 mm; 21—A. (Cap.) hilaris Gory, female, 4.8 mm; 22—A. (Cap.) aterrima Kerremans, male, 7.1 mm; 23—A. (Cap.) sulcicollis Obenberger, male, 4.0 mm; 24—the same, female, 5.8 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599422/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="269">Figs. 19–24</figureCitation>
). Also the elytral sculpture is rather different from that of other subgenera: longitudinal rows of punctures (
<figureCitation box="[1172,1300,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–24" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1851,1874]" captionTargetBox="[165,1426,219,1796]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1435,205,1810]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 13–24. Anthaxia, dorsal aspect. 13—Anthaxia (Melanthaxia) kochi Obenberger, male, 6.5 mm; 14- A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug), male, 6.1 mm; 15—A. (R.) congolana Kerremans, male, 11.0 mm; 16—A. (R.) marginifera metallescens Bílý, male, 9.1 mm; 17—A. (Merocratus) miranda Deyrolle, female, 8.0 mm; 18—A. (Thailandica.) rondoni Baudon, 5.5 mm; 19—A. (Capanthaxia) capensis Kerremans, lectotype, 3.9 mm; 20—the same, male, blue form, 4.5 mm; 21—A. (Cap.) hilaris Gory, female, 4.8 mm; 22—A. (Cap.) aterrima Kerremans, male, 7.1 mm; 23—A. (Cap.) sulcicollis Obenberger, male, 4.0 mm; 24—the same, female, 5.8 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599422/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="269">Fig. 19, 20</figureCitation>
), transverse rugae (
